Completely blown away by my experience at Gary Danko! Came here for Valentines Day dinner - best dinner I've had in a long time! The BF didn't really have an appetite, so we opted for the 3 and 4 course options - it ended up being more than enough food! The waiter started by explaining how the restaurant works. You choose between a 3, 4, or 5 course dinner, and basically mix and match different items on the menu to make your own custom menu. You're not obligated to select one item out of each of the categories (appetizer, sea, meats & game, dessert), but they recommend that you select from different parts of the menu! We ordered: Foie gras - absolutely DELICIOUS. Relatively large portion of seared foie gras served with carmelized onions and greens. Perfect way to start the meal. Seared scallops: plump scallops served with a lotus root chip and a delicious lentil sauce. Crab salad - super fresh crab, definitely on the lighter side. Lobster - this was the BF's favorite. Super tender, savory lobster over a bed of pureed potatoes. Lobster done right! Quail with foie - The quail meat was a little on the dryer side, but the stuffing and sauce were delicious. Bison - Served rare over a bed of spaetzle with these AMAZING mushrooms on top. To die for. Grand Marnier Souffle - this was the perfect dessert to end our meal! Creamsicle ice cream with fluffly souffle. So good. The after dessert desserts were a nice treat as well - we couldn't touch them because we were so stuffed, but they were a good snack the next day! Their breakfast treats were a nice touch as well - we received banana cream cheese cake to munch on the next morning. Overall a perfect dinner!

An amazing experience. From the bar to the menu to the service - all of it, exceptional. We chose the five course menu and wine tasting. Ca c'est superbe! I started my meal with a poached egg over fried sweetbreads. Think I cried, no, I definitely cried. The egg was poached to perfection, holding its shape but the yolk was runny, warm and delicious. Upon entry, my family and I were greeting by several hosts and hostesses and were offered a coat check. After, they lead us into the back in the private room (we were a party of 10). Wow! The room was beautifully decorated with fresh flowers and with amazing table decorum. Everything about this place was spectacular. This restaurant does not have an 'a la carte' type of menu. Instead, each individual can choose a 3-course, 4-course, or 5-course meal at $85, $101, or $119 respectively. Once you decide the number of courses, you can choose any dishes you want. If you want three entrees, you can. Three appetizers? Why not. They also change the portion sizes of the dishes depending on which #-courses you choose. I'm not going to go into every single dish that we got (that would take a whole days worth of description!) But I DEFINITELY recommend the Seared Foie Gras as an appetizer, and the Lemon Peppered Duck Breast as the entree. They were my personal favs hands down. However, they do update their menu once every couple months, so maybe my recommendations won't be too helpful. The plating for all the dishes were phenomenal as well. I didn't even want to eat it because they looked too beautiful to be ruined. I loved every part of this evening, and definitely can't wait to come back. Well done, San Francisco! You got a real treasure here. Other recommendations: - Seared Sea Scallops - Roast Quail & quinoa (it's was a much bigger portion than expected) - Roast Maine Lobster - Chocolate Souffle (dessert)

Awesome! Great service, amazing food, fantastic wine list with ample selection of 1/2 bottles complimentary to multi course menus!

Gary Danko provides top-notch service, a wide variety of appetizers, mains (seafood, meat, and poultry), and desserts, and a very extensive wine and cocktails menu. Put all these together in an overly floral, modern, and romantic setting, and you have the perfect recipe for a lovely dining experience. The 3-course menu starts at $81, and each additional course is an additional $18. Our server, Lila, informed us that the courses are full-sized and that the 5-course is standard. But we came hungry and as naive first-timers who eat with our eyes, we both ordered a 6-course and were extremely stuffed at the end of the night. The seared foie gras with caramelized onions and peaches appetizer was delicious. The soft and delicate fatty liver was absolutely buttery and velvety. Pairing it with caramelized onions and peaches helped mellow the foie gras' richness, but I wished it also came with some sort of toasted bread to help tone down the entire dish. The roasted Maine lobster with potato puree, chanterelle mushrooms, corn, and fresh tarragon was my favorite dish of the night. The lobster was fresh and meaty, but not overwhelmed by the buttery and rich potato puree. The salmon medallion was fresh, but not amazing. The dilled cucumbers stood out the most with its light and refreshing taste, and the horseradish crust, albeit a bit salty, added a mild vinegary taste that wasn't too overpowering. The seared beef filet was a generous portion, cooked to a perfect medium to my liking, and it was very tender. But much to my surprise, the portion was a little too large for me, as I became quickly tired of it. The side of swiss chard was extremely bitter and I didn't feel that it complemented well with the beef. They should've been blanched in salty water to help eliminate all that bitter taste. For an additional $6, the prepared tableside flambéed cherries with mascarpone-filled crepes dessert was an entertaining and delicious treat. The crepes were fluffy and the mascarpone was very mild, not too rich. The cherries, oatmeal-graham cracker streusel, and caramel sauce pulled the whole dish together with tart and sweet flavors. Overall, I felt indifferent about the food. Quality and presentation were nice, but taste wasn't outstanding. On the other hand, service and ambiance were impeccable. Servers and hosts opening main doors and bathroom doors for you, servers neatly folding your napkin when you leave the table, and servers with food cover domes by your table if your food arrived but you stepped away. Even the bathroom is gorgeous! Parking is very difficult in the neighborhood, and if you're lucky enough to find a space, note that there's a 2-hour time limit before 8pm. So if you dine at 6pm, you probably wouldn't be out of the restaurant within 2 hours. In all, I'm glad I finally tried Gary Danko, and even though I wasn't too happy with the big splurge, I was very content with the overall dining experience.

I have been waiting MONTHS to have time to come here with my boyfriend. We finally took a weekend off for my birthday weekend and came here for dinner on a Friday night. As soon as you walk in, you are immediately overcome with a warm and dark, high-end, romantic feeling. I fell in love already. We made a reservation about two weeks ago and when we went to check-in with the hostess, it seemed like they had lost our reservation..? They told us to just stand to the side and that our table is "getting ready". Shouldn't our table have already been ready before we arrived..? They finally sat us down after about 10 minutes...next to a wall and where waiters walk back and forth around. Great. It took them another 10 minutes to bring us a menu. We first started with some drinks and that of course took forever..again. FINALLY they came by to take our order. The two of us got the 4 course. I am going to do my best to remember exactly what I ordered: 1) Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Zucchini Pearls, Leeks and Lettuce Cream--not what I was expecting. This dish definitely did not match with my taste. I took one bite and my boyfriend had the rest of it. 2) Seared Sea Scallops with Lentils, Roasted Peppers, Potatoes, Parsley and Madras Curry Vinaigrette--this was actually really good. Perfectly seared scallops with great seasoning and flavor that paired well with the entire dish. 3) Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb with Summer Vegetable Tian and Polenta--as I was eating my food, I looked over to my boyfriend's seared filet and immediately regretted getting the lamb. I typically LOVE lamb but I just did not like this one. The seasoning and sides did not pair well for my palate. 4) Lemon Soufflé Cake with Crème Fraîche Panna Cotta and Raspberry Sorbet--good. That's all I can say. It wasn't amazing or terrific, but just simply good. The staff was kind enough to bring out a cake and small cookies since I was celebrating my birthday there which I really appreciated. I believe the total for two 4-courses was about $360, including drinks. For the upscale ambiance, I think the prices are quite reasonable. Maybe I just need to go back and try other items on the menu. Will possibly go back.

    Upon entry, my family and I were greeting by several hosts and hostesses and were offered a coat check. After, they lead us into the back in the private room (we were a party of 10). Wow! The room was beautifully decorated with fresh flowers and with amazing table decorum. Everything about this place was spectacular.

    This restaurant does not have an 'a la carte' type of menu. Instead, each individual can choose a 3-course, 4-course, or 5-course meal at $85, $101, or $119 respectively. Once you decide the number of courses, you can choose any dishes you want. If you want three entrees, you can. Three appetizers? Why not. They also change the portion sizes of the dishes depending on which #-courses you choose.

    I'm not going to go into every single dish that we got (that would take a whole days worth of description!) But I DEFINITELY recommend the Seared Foie Gras as an appetizer, and the Lemon Peppered Duck Breast as the entree. They were my personal favs hands down. However, they do update their menu once every couple months, so maybe my recommendations won't be too helpful. The plating for all the dishes were phenomenal as well. I didn't even want to eat it because they looked too beautiful to be ruined. I loved every part of this evening, and definitely can't wait to come back. Well done, San Francisco! You got a real treasure here.

    Other recommendations:
    - Seared Sea Scallops
    - Roast Quail & quinoa (it's was a much bigger portion than expected)
    - Roast Maine Lobster
    - Chocolate Souffle (dessert)

  • Priscilla W.
    San Francisco, CA

    Embed review

    10/3/2015

    10 photos

    1 check-in

    Gary Danko provides top-notch service, a wide variety of appetizers, mains (seafood, meat, and poultry), and desserts, and a very extensive wine and cocktails menu. Put all these together in an overly floral, modern, and romantic setting, and you have the perfect recipe for a lovely dining experience.

    The 3-course menu starts at $81, and each additional course is an additional $18. Our server, Lila, informed us that the courses are full-sized and that the 5-course is standard. But we came hungry and as naive first-timers who eat with our eyes, we both ordered a 6-course and were extremely stuffed at the end of the night.

    The seared foie gras with caramelized onions and peaches appetizer was delicious. The soft and delicate fatty liver was absolutely buttery and velvety. Pairing it with caramelized onions and peaches helped mellow the foie gras' richness, but I wished it also came with some sort of toasted bread to help tone down the entire dish.

    The roasted Maine lobster with potato puree, chanterelle mushrooms, corn, and fresh tarragon was my favorite dish of the night. The lobster was fresh and meaty, but not overwhelmed by the buttery and rich potato puree.

    The salmon medallion was fresh, but not amazing. The dilled cucumbers stood out the most with its light and refreshing taste, and the horseradish crust, albeit a bit salty, added a mild vinegary taste that wasn't too overpowering.

    The seared beef filet was a generous portion, cooked to a perfect medium to my liking, and it was very tender. But much to my surprise, the portion was a little too large for me, as I became quickly tired of it. The side of swiss chard was extremely bitter and I didn't feel that it complemented well with the beef. They should've been blanched in salty water to help eliminate all that bitter taste.

    For an additional $6, the prepared tableside flambéed cherries with mascarpone-filled crepes dessert was an entertaining and delicious treat. The crepes were fluffy and the mascarpone was very mild, not too rich. The cherries, oatmeal-graham cracker streusel, and caramel sauce pulled the whole dish together with tart and sweet flavors.

    Overall, I felt indifferent about the food. Quality and presentation were nice, but taste wasn't outstanding. On the other hand, service and ambiance were impeccable. Servers and hosts opening main doors and bathroom doors for you, servers neatly folding your napkin when you leave the table, and servers with food cover domes by your table if your food arrived but you stepped away. Even the bathroom is gorgeous! Parking is very difficult in the neighborhood, and if you're lucky enough to find a space, note that there's a 2-hour time limit before 8pm. So if you dine at 6pm, you probably wouldn't be out of the restaurant within 2 hours. In all, I'm glad I finally tried Gary Danko, and even though I wasn't too happy with the big splurge, I was very content with the overall dining experience.

    7/23/2017

    I have been waiting MONTHS to have time to come here with my boyfriend. We finally took a weekend off for my birthday weekend and came here for dinner on a Friday night. As soon as you walk in, you are immediately overcome with a warm and dark, high-end, romantic feeling. I fell in love already. We made a reservation about two weeks ago and when we went to check-in with the hostess, it seemed like they had lost our reservation..? They told us to just stand to the side and that our table is "getting ready". Shouldn't our table have already been ready before we arrived..?

    They finally sat us down after about 10 minutes...next to a wall and where waiters walk back and forth around. Great.

    It took them another 10 minutes to bring us a menu. We first started with some drinks and that of course took forever..again. FINALLY they came by to take our order.

    The two of us got the 4 course. I am going to do my best to remember exactly what I ordered:

    1) Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Zucchini Pearls, Leeks and Lettuce Cream--not what I was expecting. This dish definitely did not match with my taste. I took one bite and my boyfriend had the rest of it.

    2) Seared Sea Scallops with Lentils, Roasted Peppers, Potatoes, Parsley and Madras Curry Vinaigrette--this was actually really good. Perfectly seared scallops with great seasoning and flavor that paired well with the entire dish.

    3) Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb with Summer Vegetable Tian and Polenta--as I was eating my food, I looked over to my boyfriend's seared filet and immediately regretted getting the lamb. I typically LOVE lamb but I just did not like this one. The seasoning and sides did not pair well for my palate.

    4) Lemon Soufflé Cake with Crème Fraîche Panna Cotta and Raspberry Sorbet--good. That's all I can say. It wasn't amazing or terrific, but just simply good.

    The staff was kind enough to bring out a cake and small cookies since I was celebrating my birthday there which I really appreciated.

    I believe the total for two 4-courses was about $360, including drinks. For the upscale ambiance, I think the prices are quite reasonable. Maybe I just need to go back and try other items on the menu. Will possibly go back.
